Some initial recommendations for servers are as follows:


§5§lGeneral§r
§cKill§r
Do not type/@kill @e as you will murder the invisible armor stands that this mod relies on in order to position quest rewards, and then you will be in a huge mess.

How do you get out of that mess? Well. The basics go something like this:

First, teleport everyone home with 
§7/island home
/tp @a ~ 89 ~§r

Armor stands can be summoned wi§§th §7
/execute @a ~ ~ ~ summon armor_stand ~ 87 ~ {NoGravity:1,NoBasePlate:1,Invulnerable:1,Invisible:1,Tags:["IslandCenter"]}§r

They are then assigned an ID score via the scoreboard that is identical to their player's ID score, which may be achieved with something like... 
§7/execute @e[type=armor_stand,tag="IslandCenter"] ~ ~ ~ scoreboard players operation @s ID = @p ID

§rNote that this wont restore the armor stands of anyone not online, and if for some reason their base was chunk loaded, their armor stand will be dead dead dead. 

Consider creating a new objective named 'armor fixed' and use a repeating command block or other means of running functions that will teleport all newly joined players to their base, check for a nearby armor stand (or simply destroy it since you'll be making a new one) and then create a properly positioned armor stand.

§5§lVoid Island Control§r
§cMaster ball§r
/island visit should be disabled, /tp should be disabled, and /tpa commands should be restricted until the player has passed the masterball quest at the beginning of the game, after which their gamestage score will be raised to 1. This is to prevent players from working together to duplicate masterballs. (masterballs are automatically deleted if brought to spawn in the possession of a player in gamestage 0 and can be recovered once on their home island via the 'mistakes were made' questline)

§cMessy Commands§r
/island home is a vital command for targeting teleportions to the player's island. But, if run alone it will teleport them BELOW their island. To work, it must always be accompanied by a /tp ~ 89 ~ (You can see this in the command blocks at spawn and the repeatable quest in the questbook) You can't disable /island home using the VoidIslandControl config without breaking everything, but if you can hide it from the players using a server plug-in, that would be ideal. (The reason the players are teleported below their island has to do with our hacky workaround for preventing structures from having a minimum Y value of 86.)

§cOwn Plugin? Sure!§r
You are welcome to replace VoidIslandControl with your own plug-in appropriate to managing skyblock worlds. There are even some good reasons to do that.

VoidIslandControl is responsible for a number of 'weird bugs,' like minimum structure heights and the suspiciously missing fog and gravity modifications for Ultra Space. The workaround for some of these bugs is wonky, and for others its nonexistant.

A structure file for the starting islands and main island is found inside /config/voidislandcontrolstructures, and both can also be created with the /pillar commands§5§r.

§5§lPixelmon§r
§cNPC Overload
§rThe questbook encourages players to create new villagers.

Once in awhile you are going to get a problematic players who hoards far too many villagers. Villagers cannot be destroyed with /kill, and the useage of /pokenpckill will kill all villagers on all loaded chunks and cannot be tamed using selectors, which, thanks to RF Tools, may be many many many more villagers than you are emotionally prepared to nuke.

When you restart servers, almost all chunk loaders stop working and have to be revisted to resume working, which may help you with focusing your /pokenpckill

You can use the item, the NPC Editor, to despawn specific unwanted NPCs. 

It is recommended you test server plug-ins on NPCs to ensure you have a way of target-editing a large number of NPCs in a single place, and that you've warned players not to hoard more than X amount of NPCs.

§5§lRF Tools
§cToo many dimensions!
§rConsider limiting the amount of fully custom dimensions available to each player and routinely wiping all rftools dimensions (while making it very clear to players that dimensions are meant to be wiped.)

Alternatively, when you restart servers, almost all chunk loaders stop working and have to be revisted to resume working, which may help you reduce server load.

We do not recommend enabling the Builder (+ Quarry) for gameplay reasons. The modpack is a Pixelmon Skyblock, and adding a Quarry to RFTools Dimensions worlds turns the experience of playing back into vanilla minecraft.

§cPokemon in Dimensions§r
Pokemon have to be configured to spawn in a dimension in the /config/pixelmon/BetterSpawnerConfigjson folder. As I have not yet gotten around to implementing rftools questlines, I have not fully tested this, but one presumes a way of ensuring Pokemon spawn in all dimensions is to simply start at the dimension number RFTools will begin at, and begin entering them, one at a time, up to 300 dimensions or so; after that, wipe dimension occasionally to keep the amount of dimensions low enough that they are always covered by the dimension range you inputed.

You have noticed your 'man made' outdoor structural blocks will attract different variety of §dPorygon§r, some at night and some during the day. You are uncertain why the Porygon do not want to come inside, but they appear very agitated.

§cDo you want to swap out Void Island Control in Singleplayer?
§r
§5Void Island Control§r was only used because it was a client-side mod that allowed for both singleplayer and multiplayer void island experiences. It has a lot of bugs. We've worked around most of them.

§cGet familiar with the two core pack structures§r

Play the first few quests. Fall off the island at least once. Examine the pack and determine the coordinates at which you want to spawn both the §bmain island, §rand your individual '§bghost island.' §r

These two key structures exist in §5/config/voidislandcontrolstructures, §rand can also be quickly spawned in, in-game, through §a/pillar §rcommands (which spawn in structures from the pillar folder).

Both islands are y-level sensitive. The main island §e(mainisland.nbt)§r is meant to be at world center, with a /tp 0 89 0 dropping the player off right in the middle of the chalice.

The ghost island §e(ghostisland.nbt)§r can be put anywhere(x/z), but it's top block must be at y=88. It is triggered to spawn at y=60 with a lot of empty buffer space beneathe it to fix §oanother§r Void Island Control bug.

The two structures come packed with commands that make the rest of the quest book work. For best results, §c§bstand directly above or below the center of the ghost island as you spawn it.§r Otherwise everything will be shifted (courtesy of the x/z placement of an invisible and highly important armor stand.)

If you ever want to see the commands the ghost island is running, presumably so you can edit them, spawn in §eghostislandcommand.nbt§r, which doesn't self-delete its commands.

§cWhat to replace the mod with?§r

You can replace §5Void Island Control§r with a different singleplayer void creator, such as the §bOTG (Open Terrain Editor) VOID §rtemplate (2 installs), or a §aserver plug-in§r (if you know how to run a dedicated server). You can also try simply removing §5Void Island Control§r after creating a world and deleting the ultra space dimension folder to regenerate it (untested).

§cWhat commands will need fixing?§r

The main island uses one /island home command to target teleportation out to the islands. Replace this with the correct coordinates of your island.

The ghost island centers all future commands around itself with an invisible armor stand. That armor stand will appear relative to where the player is when the ghost island spawns in, so its imperative the player be standing on top of the center of where the ghost island is spawning in at.
§

Your mother spent a lot of time teaching you family recipes for potion-making. Not only do you know how to make §dpotions of regeneration§r, but you know how to make §bpixelmon potions§r for healing your Pokemon!

When it comes to brewing, there are two ways of going about it:
1. §cCauldron Brewing§r
2. §6Brewing Stand Brewing§r

Cauldron Brewing is §einstantaneous, §rlower tech, §rand does not require blaze powder, but the recipes are slightly different and often the yield is smaller. You will have to build an open fire, but it will only have to stay lit for a second.
Brewing Stand Brewing takes time and requires §6Blaze Powder§r, but the yield is typically higher.

You believe you are going to get roughly equal yield from your family §bPotion§r recipe however, which should turn a single §aOran Berry§r into three potions! That's 6x the healing power!

This Quest Line will be divided into Materials and Goals.

(Check the JEI for recipes!)

So, what's the plan for §cMaking Pokeballs?

§rSo far, you don't have one! 

To produce Pokeballs, you will need:
1. [§aEASY§r] Pink Apricorns. 
2. [      ] A Hammer
3. [§cHARD§r] A Pokemon Anvil
4. [§aEASY§r] Stone Buttons
5. [      ] Metal disks, to make the bottom of each Pokeball


While traditionally made with iron, some of these objects can be made with sustitutes. §bCrystal§r, which is easily farmed from Bunnelby, can be turned into a §bHammer. §6Aluminum §rcan be used to make §6Metal Disks§r. But there is no replacing the iron in a §7Pokemon Anvil. §r

You need §e32 Ingots of Iron§,.§r

And that? That's not going to happen any time soon. The only "common" underground Pokemon who drops iron is §7Aron,§r who is not truly common and only drops nuggets. 

Hmm. You know what? there are other ways to get Pokemon. Arceus seems to want to bury you in §dbaby Pokemon§r. Furthermore, you think you can §csalvage§r Pokeballs from spare parts.

§o

The more you build up a habitat for §7underground §rPokemon to latch on to, the more it occurs to you that you are seeing a wide variety of Pokemon §aabove§r ground.

Today you placed down §9water§r and a §9Frillish§r floated on by and landed in it! Frillish are §bOcean §rpokemon! What was a Frillish doing here?!

It begins to occur to you that the §5destruction of the world§r doesn't care what §5Biome §rthis used to be. Pokemon floating about in the void are now latching onto anything you build that's familiar to them!

You start to wonder if §eevery Y level §rand §aevery combination§r of conditions might attract slightly different Pokemon.

What happens if you build a house? Will domestic Pokemon like §dStufful§r or §dHatenna§r latch on and move in? Does the house have to be high above where the 'ground' used to be?

Are there §bflying§r Pokemon out here? Birds? Where? High up? You fear only the strongest, luckiest, or most resilient have survived, but you will need to check.

At several different elevations, try to build an indoor enclosure. You are curious about what kind of Pokemon you will find.

First, try building an indoor enclosure at Y levels greater than 120.

Pokemon are multiplying in the §6habitats§r you've built for them. Since §dthe entire world has been destroyed§r, there are obviously §cno ores§r. The only sources you have of earthen materials are from §6harvesting §rPokemon.

This Questline will be divided into two major parts:

§bA) Materials§r
§2§aB) Goals§r

It seems that, for the most part, Pokemon are spawning underground at low Y levels in the way you would naturally expect. This is good! It means you can make a §blist of important materials§r and identify the §bmost common§r Pokemon that can drop those materials! In the meantime, you can also identify important §agoals§r, like §aforging Pokeballs§r and §abuilding a PC.

You need §4Redstone §rfor a variety of reasons, from extending potions to creating circuitry for PCs, and the best place to harvest it from is Ghostly Computers: The §eRotom.§r

You have noticed an assortment of §a§eRotom §rare gathering in different places. Rotom are §eelectric §rtype Pokemon that possess different objects, like washing machines and lawmowers, giving them access to a second typing. 

If you think very hard, you think these rules for Rotom's spotty appearance may make sense:

1. §eRotom §rseems to spawn at low Y levels, in 'man made shelters,' not caves.
2. §cRotom Heat§r seems to spawn indoors at night.
3. §7Rotom Fan §rseems to spawn indoors during the day.
4. §bRotom Frost§r seems to spawn indoors all the time.
5. §9Rotom Wash§r seems to spawn out of doors on manmade structures.
6. §aRotom Mow §rseems to spawn out of doors on land blocks like grass and stone.

You aren't sure which of these Rotoms will be the easiest to pursue. You could try and summon (or wait for) a rainstorm to drive all the §aBurmy§r into hiding and hope §aRotom Mow§r is more common, or you could try building a §6indoor shelter at a Y level below 60,§r sort of like a scary mining camp or underground bunker, and see if §eRegular Rotom§r shows up. Or you could just hang out inside at normal Y level and wait!

Another Pokemon famously gathers around power plants, and can be deconstructed for §7Iron§r and §6Aluminum.§r This Pokemon is §7§eMagnemite§r, and you are sure that it-- a Pokemon that can levitate-- must have survived the §5cataclysm!§r

But you don't see Magnemite anywhere... 

Hmm. Magnemite also loves §emountains§r, and §bstorms. §rYou decide that what you are going to do is this:

1. Build a §e§lLightning Rod§r
2. Climb to a great height of Y greater than §a150.§r
3. Place down the Lightning Rod on an §9outdoors, man made structure§r
4. Hope that's enough, and/or hope it storms!

You don't actually know if there are any §cVoltorb §rout there any more, but you have to hope!  Voltorb can be harvested for Pokeball parts, and if you can find enough of them, you can reassemble a Pokeball with the help of a §7Stone Button.§r 

To build a good §6habitat §rfor Voltorb, try building an §aindoor §renclosure at a §bslightly elevated altitude §r(Y greater than 100), somewhat like a power plant. Voltorb are attracted to large amounts of glowstone and redstone, such as §eglowstone blocks§r and §credstone blocks.

§rCaution: Voltorb are very dangerous (they are §eElectric §rtype, which can target down your Drifloon, and know Self-Destruct, which can hurt your other Pokemon). Glowstone and redstone may attract different levels of Voltorb.

Eventually you are going to run out of space in your party to holds so many §aeggs§r and §c§dPokemon.§r You need to make a §cPC§r!

There are major ingredients you require for a PC:

1. [      ] Glass (Or Sand)
2. [§aEASY§r] Redstone
3. [§aEASY§r] Glowstone
4. [§a    §r  ] Aluminum Plates

5. [§aEASY§r] Silicon
6. [§aEASY§r] Gold Nuggets

The biggest obstacle is clearly the §b§6six aluminum plates§r, as you have ideas for harvesting Glowstone and Redstone written in your materials section of this quest list. But how will you make plates? You might be able to make a hammer, but you certainly have no anvil!

§o(Check the recipe for the PC. The Silicon and Gold Nuggets are now part of its recipe through the "Machine Base" which is a simple printed circuitboard.

You have an idea for how to get §6Aluminum Plates§r without an anvil! §eTogedemaru§r is an extremely robust Pokemon you are §osure§r must have survived the §d§5Cataclysm§r. Because Togedemaru usually lives in §bmountains§r, you believe you will have to climb up quite high and provide a §anatural landscape§r for it to spawn in. Togedemaru can be harvested for §7natural aluminum plates.§r

Try climbing to a height of Y greater than §b150§r and put out a few pokey Iron Fences/Iron Bars to see if you can establish a breeding habitat for Togedemaru.

§r§o(Pay attention to the recipe for Iron Bars/Iron Fences. There is a way to make them with only nuggets instead of complete ingots.)

To get glass panes you are going to have to get six pieces of glass, which will require you to find §esix pieces of sand.§r There are a couple ways you know of to get sand. The two best appear to be these:

1. You have seen §eGalarian Yamask§r patrolling manmade structures below Y level 50 during the day. You believe these may drop sand. Yamask is attracted to sandstone carvings, so if you find a block of sandstone, place it nearby to create an ideal habitat.

2. §bShellder§r is a durable Pokemon that lives on the sea floor and may cough up sand when defeated. If any have survived, you might be able to attract it to inhabit water blocks, even running water blocks, at the bottom of a tank. Make sure you use appropriate 'land' blocks for the bottom of the tank, such as rock or dirt!

Runner ups were as folllows:

3. §7Dunsparce, §ran extremely rare underground Pokemon, sometimes coughs up sand when defeated. While too rare to search for on its own, more Dunsparce may be attracted to a habitat if you place down a block of sand. Just remember that sand falls!

4. §6Wormadam§r, may wear one of three cloaks. The §ctrash§r cloak may be recoverable for iron nuggets, and the §6sandy §rcloak may be recoverable for sand, but not always. Wormadam is an unfortunately high leve

5. §6Sandshrew§r is a durable Pokemon, but you have no idea if it has survived the §5Cataclysm §ror, if it has, where to find it.

6. §5Sandygast§r is a ghost Pokemon that can be harvested for sand, but it will only spawn on sand that already exists. If you do find a lot of sand, it might be worth it to make a little 'beach' habitat.

Using the same basic techniques you used for the §cPC,§r it should be possible to create a §cFossil Machine§r. Look at the recipes carefully, as §7Obsidian§r is §dno longer required. §rInstead, you will need to make an advance polyfiber backing for your computer screen! 

Or. Well. You need to dye some wool black with Deathbloom powder. Close enough!

You have seen some §eYamask §rrunning around at low Y levels. Yamask haunt ruined ancient artifacts. There are two variants, an ancient variant that drops §esand, §rand a more medeival variant that drops §6gold.§r 

You have worked out the Yamask you want gathers §bindoors§r at Y levels §blower than 50§r, and that it only appears at night. It also appears to be greatly attracted to sandstone; if you happen to find a block, you should place it nearby to make an ideal habitat.

Using the same basic techniques you used for the §cPC,§r it should be possible to create a §cFossil Cleaner §rand §cFossil Machine§r. Both of these recipes require a tremendous amount of aluminum plates.

You suddenly had a vision.

You believe it is from Arceus!

He seemed to ask that you bring him §aone Regular Potion of Regeneration§r and §done heal ball disk§r in a §6bowl§r.

You can do this! You §bare §rable to make disks... It's only the lids themselves you can't make, because you do not have an anvil! 

And heal ball disks are one of very few disks you can make with the resources on this island. They require §dPink§r and §lWhite§r Apricorns.

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Gathering §7Iron §ris difficult, and you may not want to waste your first ingot on a Flint and Steel. There is another option: A §cFire Charge§r.

Fire Charges are made from:
1. [§aEASY§r] Gunpowder
2. [§aEASY§r] Coal or Charcoal
3. [§aEASY§r] Blaze Powder

Fire charges are single use, and their flames will not last forever without Netherrack.

Gunpowder can be harvested from §dWhismur§r, a shy pink and yellow Pokemon that can be found underground at Y levels less than 70.

With time you should also be able to find §dKoffings§r and §bRemoraid§r to harvest it from. 

Gunpowder can be used in splash potions. (Splash potions of regeneration can be very effective early game on your Pokemon.)

It can also be used to make §cFire Charges§r.

You know it is possible to §dbrew§r in cauldrons, although you will not get as good a yield for most recipes as you do with brewing stands. In addition to standard potions, you can also brew potions for your Pokemon!

(Check the JEI for recipes!)

In order to get started, you will need a §crock cauldron§r, as wood cauldrons will simply burn.

Normally, you are §r§osure§r you can forage for §cNetherwart §rin §5ominous §rand §cevil §rbiomes, but no matter how long you search, you just haven't found any. 

You have an idea, however. There are a number of §cgiant mushroom pokemon §rwho propogate by spores, and you believe you have seen some popping out of the soil and wandering around outside and underground at your island's Y level. After taking a look at all the available species, you are pretty sure if you harvest enough §aShroomish§r you should be able to find a Netherwart. The Shroomish here do not look healthy, and only seem to come out during the§e day.§r

Like Redstone, §eGlowstone§r is associated with electric Pokemon. And very few Electric Pokemon seem to have been protected enough to survive the §5Cataclysm.§r It can be used in electronics and to enhance brews.

You've noticed many underground Pokemon seem to be right where you expect to see them.

Therefore, you think you should make a habitat for §eTynamo§r, a small eel-like pokemon that only gathers in §bUnderground Water§r. Tynamo will gather at any Y level.

Alternatively, you think you have seen glowing lights in the distance at night; an open field in the evening might attract §aIllumise§r or §aVolbeat, §rif any have survived.

§6Soul Sand's §rprimary usage is for growing §cNetherwart.§r It can be dropped by §6Galarian Yamask, §rwho gather on Manmade structures at low Y values, and by §5Gastly, §rwho will gather anywhere around here indoors, outdoors, or underground. Gastly absolutely must have a §6light limit of exactly zero to spawn.§r No light at all, Gastly is a vampire made from the very essence of darkness!

§6Blaze Powder's §rprimary usage is for creating §cFire Charges§r or fueling a §6Brewing Stand.§r It can also be used in Strength potions, but you doubt you need those with Pokemon helping you out!

You have an idea of where to find it: You are surrounded by ghosts, and §5Litwick§r, the candle Pokemon, can be harvested for Blaze Powder. Litwick prefers to stay §bindoors§r to protect it from wind and rain, and it is attracted to §4§etorches§r and §estreet lights§r. You have a street light you could repurpose!

§r§o§c(WARNING: Take anti-fire precautions, as fire spread is not disabled!)§r

At times like these, potions of §6Night Vision§r make it much easier to see, especially amid all the fog!

Potions of Night Vision are two-stage potions, just like Potions of Regeneration. First, a §cnetherwart§r must be used to make an Awkward Portion. Then, a §eGolden Carrot§r must be added. Ensure you are always working with the right amount of liquid!

Extend your potion of Night Vision by adding §cRedstone§r in order to complete this quest!
§6Magma Cream's §rprimary usage is for creating §cPotions of Fire Resistance§r. It can be created using blaze powder and Slime.

§aSlime§r is an important ingredient for creating §7§6Magma Cream§r, §aSticky Pistons§r, and ultimately the §4Mechanical Anvil§r. It's also sticky and bouncy and fun to play with. 

You believe you have seen a number of Pokemon such as §5Grimer§r and §aGulpin§r from which Slime can be harvested. You may have even seen a Pyukumuku.

§cApples§r are always important resources, not only because they can be eaten, but because they can be crafted into powerful §6golden apples§r. Your elders from the Skyblocks told you that golden apples are important for rescuing sick or ill civillians. You might want to establish a place you can harvest them!

Oak trees do not grew well here, but you think it might be possible to find a stronger 'Flowering Oak' or 'Dark Oak' sapling with time. 

Try looking for a Wurmple, or Applin.

You can create a weak lure with four iron bars, three of which are used to make the chain, and §9two sapphires§r. Weak lures are extremely useful when you are trying to lure out the correct Pokemon to harvest materials from. 

Weak lures increase the chance a Pokemon of a given type spawns by 50%

You add a leppa and oran berry to them, as well as a berry associated with the correct element.

You know that Onix can be made from different kinds of ores, such as Bauxite and Cole. You've even have heard of a mythical §bCrystal Onix§r which is made from crystal and gemstone. 

However you have no idea where you would find a Crystal Onix. You clearly haven't found any deep under the ground. You remember stories about them being in little caves on the tippy top of the tallest mountain peaks. 

Try crafting edible §9boulders§r from stone and clay to attract them

Take advantage of their magnetic wayfinding abilities by placing magnetic blocks like §credstone§r, §eglowstone§r§r, and §7iron§r.

You know that §9§7Onix §rcan be made from different kinds of ores, such as Bauxite and Coal. You know they are found deep below the earth, but that they are extremely rare. 

Onix need stones for food, which means any that survived the Cataclysm and are floating through the void should be attracted to your underground habitats at Y levels lower than 50. 

Try crafting edible §9boulders§r from stone and clay to attract them

Take advantage of their magnetic wayfinding abilities by placing magnetic blocks like §credstone§r, §eglowstone§r§r, and §7iron§r.

While some other Pokemon lurking in various habitats, like Togedameru and Chinchou, can drop glowstone, you believe you can increase the number of §eTynamo§r in a location by adding a block of §eglowstone§r. Tynamo's evolved forms are very high level; be wary of them if they appear!

Just like in any Skyblock, it is possible to build §amob drop towers§r. In this case, the purpose of the mob drop towers wouldn't be to hurt the mobs, but rather to ferry them away from a habitat so that more things have room to appear there.

You can make primitive 'water drop towers' by suspending water high up in the air and creating a platform to catch everything. Pokemon can only spawn if they are a certain distance away from other Pokemon, which means they will spawn high up in the water, drop to the pool/platform below, and collect there in large numbers.

In addition to water, there are other tools you can use for moving around pixelmon, villagers, or other mobs. 

You should try to create a few, both to help you control spawns, and in case you need to move some villagers down the line!

The first lure you create needs to be a Weak Steel Lure. This lure will increase the rate steel pokemon, Like §7Aron§r and §eTogedameru§r and §e§dBronzor§r spawn, by 50%

To create the lure, you will need to collect:
1. [§aDONE§r] Your empty Iron Lure. 
2. [§aEASY§r] An Oran Berry
3. [§aEASY§r] A Leppa Berry
4. [      ] A §7Babiri Berry§r (The steel-typed berry)

You believe that you can find a §7Babiri §rberry being carried by a §dClefairy§r. You will need to get at least one, and perhaps start a Babiri berry bush so you can easily harvest more.

Create your first Steel Lure as detailed in the JEI! When you are at the correct Y-Level for your Steel pokemon to spawn, equip it.


Lures are temporary, lasting only a short duration after being equipped in the inventory. Once the aroma has faded, the lure turns back into an empty Iron Lure, and can be filled with berries again. 

§o(The recipe for the lure has been changed for this pack)

All lures you create require the Oran and Leppa berry, and differ only by their typed berry. 

To improve the spawning of Tynamo (Glowstone) or Votorb (Pokeball Pieces) you can create an Electric Lure from a §eWacan§r berry.


To do this, you will need to figure out where you might be able to find §9Tentacool§r or §9Tentacruel§r, as you believe they may hold §eWacan §rberries. Try looking amoung your exploration notes.

All around you are ghosts and bugs; Normal Pokemon and Flying Pokemon are rare by comparison! If you can crate normal or flying lures, you might be able to harvest more of those kinds of Pokemon. To do that, you'll need the right berries.

You think that you can find the §eChilan Berry§r off wild §bHoothoot§r, if any have survived. The §9Coba§r berry may be carried by fighting Pokemon such as §cTimburr§r.

You have very few Fire Pokemon gathering on your island. You have seen some undead drowned Rapidash and you are not sure if they count. But a fire lure, which you can create by haresting an §cOcca Berry§r from a §aFerroseed§r should help you track down those few elusive fire Pokemon.

While you are greatful to have any Pokeballs at all, and Heal Balls have the small advantage of not forcing you to rest before you can use a new Pokemon, no Pokeball you can make with pink apricorns is particularly helpful for catching tough Pokemon. 

It looks like you may be able to harvest some §bNet Ball Lids§r, which have an advantage against Bug and Water type Pokemon. You sould check your Exploration notes for more information!

When they said you needed to "Catch them all" I don't think they meant the §r§oberries§r, but it is true that having a berry of each elemental type equips you to create lures, and lures can definitely be used to help you "Catch them all!"

In order to track down which Pokemon may have each berry, you will need to look at each berry in the JEI.

Some Pokemon will be more difficult to track down than others. Check your Exploration Notes to find some of the harder ones!

Some of hardest to find Pokemon on your list might be §dNoibat§o§r, carrier of the §bYache§r berry. If you remember the stories correctly, Noibats spawn underground at any Y level, but §oonly §r if conditions are completely pitch black with no light whatsoever, similar to Gastly.  

(You may also find Woobats will spawn underground in lightless conditions, allowing you to farm some wool!)

The §6§aInfuser §ris a machine that can be used to create §6incense§r, powered §dgems§r, special §9drinks§r, and §bvitamins§r.

You only really need one infuser running at a time, but you should probably carefully pick up the one Arceus gave you and put it in a more sensible position.

§dDrifloon §rand your other Pokemon appear to be very happy with all the nutritious berries and supplements you have been working on. You awoke last night from a dream in which Arceus instructed you to offer him different ingredients mixed with plain §efeathers§r. You think he may be willing to bless you with the important Health, Muscle, Defense, Genius, Clever, and Swift feathers you need in order to infuse more vitamins!

§eSitrus§r berries are extremely important. Not only do they heal much more than §9Oran Berries§r, but they can be added to Pokemon §9Potions§r to improve them into §dSuper Potions§r. 

Furthermore, Sitrus Berries can be added to something called a 'Health Wing in the infuser, transforming them into Vitamin "§cHP Up§r."

Sitrus berries are usually carried by Exeggcute, but you are uncertain such a fragile pokemon could have survived the cataclysm. Instead, you believe they may also be carried by §dSwirlix§r, if you can figure out how to attract one.

Iron is indeed rare. Rarer than almost all other metals and gems.

This must be a sign from Arceus that you are meant to hatch a wide variety of baby Pokemon for the early game, instead of being free to catch whatever Pokemon you fancy!

§o(Iron is intentionally gated to promote different gameplay styles, and to 'force' you to try playing with different Pokemon. Attempting to grind iron will lead to acute boredom.)

With all this sinistea everywhere, you are becoming something of a tea expert. You remember your gran enjoyed brewing §cRoserade Tea§r for her Pokemon, and you believe it can be made with Fresh Water and a §cRazz §rberry.

It's possible to harvest §bFresh Water§r from some Pokemon that is so rich with natural vitamins and minerals that it can be used to heal Pokemon! Of all the Pokemon you see most easily available, you believe the easiest Pokemon to harvest it from may be Surskit. 

You also think Fresh Water may be usable in other recipes, so it might be best not to use it all up.

It's possible to harvest §bMoomoo Milk§r from some Pokemon, but you doubt that any Moomoo have survived the cataclysm. However, if you manage to find some light and frothy Milcery, you might be able to find one made of Moomoo Milk and harvest it!

You also think§b Moomoo Milk §rmay be usable in other recipes, so it might be best not to use it all up.

It's possible to use §bFresh Water§r to make §bSoda Pop§r! Combine Fresh Water, sugar, and brittle bones in a crafting grid.  Where do you get those incredients? Hmm. Well you can likely get brittle bones from normal bones, somehow.

It's possible to use §bFresh Water§r to make §eLemonade§r! Combine Fresh Water, sugar, and §edandelion yellow§r in a crafting grid.  Where do you get those incredients? Hmm. Well you can likely get dandelions from some kind of floating, flying flower or fairy pokemon.

With all this sinistea everywhere, you are becoming something of a coffee expert. You remember your grampa enjoyed brewing §cKomala Coffee§r for his Pokemon, and you believe it can be made with Fresh Water and §cCocoa.

One time when you were on vacation with your parents, you got to squeeze fresh §ePinap juice! §rYou don't see any Pinap plants here, and they are notoriously hard to raise, but perhaps you can find some low level bug pokemon who have hoarded away a yummy §ePinap berry§r or two?

Your Nana used to make famous §cSkitty Smoothies§r out of §eNanab berries§r when you were little. §rYou don't see any Nanab plants here, and they are notoriously hard to raise, but perhaps you can find some low level bug pokemon who have hoarded away a yummy berry or two and make yourselfa smoothie?
Your Papa used to make hot §cTapu Cocoas §rout of Moomoo milk and cocoa during the holidays. §rYou wonder if you can recreate his recipe!

§bKelpsy§r berries are extremely important for EV-training pokemon, which is something your Mom explained to you one time. A calculator was involved. Uh. Well, anyway, Kelpsy berries can be fed straight to a pokemon to decrease their attack. Or they can be added to something called a 'Muscle Feather' in the infuser, transforming them into Vitamin "§cProtein§r."

Because of their dual nature, able to decrease attack or increase it, they are sometimes held by strong physical attackers, and sometimes held by frail special attackers.

Normally you would look for the 'Hitmon' family for these berries, but now you think your only hope might be some kind of snow-based Pokemon that'll gather at very high altitudes. Maybe §bVanillite§r?

§eQualot§r berries are extremely important for EV-training pokemon. Qualot berries can be fed straight to a pokemon to decrease their defense. Or they can be added to something called a 'Resist Feather' in the infuser, transforming them into Vitamin "§cIron§r."

You think Qualot berries can be found in the possession of §eTogedemaru§r, another pokemon that lives at high altitudes. You should check your explorer notes, perhaps following the upward trail of outdoor exploration goals.

§aHondew §rberries are extremely important for EV-training pokemon. They berries can be fed straight to a pokemon to decrease their special attack. Or they can be added to something called a 'Genius Feather' in the infuser, transforming them into Vitamin "§cCalcium§r."

You think Hondew berries are a rare drop of the pokemon §aSewaddle§r and its evolutionary line. You seem to remember they are a treetop Pokemon. Perhaps something in your explorers notes will help.

§eGrepa §rberries are extremely important for EV-training pokemon. They berries can be fed straight to a pokemon to decrease their special defense. Or they can be added to something called a 'Clever Feather' in the infuser, transforming them into Vitamin "§cZinc§r."

You aren't sure if anything has survived that can drop Grepa berries, but you need to look. Typically Chansey carries them, but those were exceptionally rare even before the planet was destroyed. §cSentret§r commonly had Grepa berries. It doesn't seem like many squirrel pokemon have survived, but then again you did find Burmy and Pineco! Maybe if you prepare some tree tops and pray?

§cTamato §rberries are extremely important for EV-training pokemon. They berries can be fed straight to a pokemon to decrease their speed. Or they can be added to something called a 'Genius Feather' in the infuser, transforming them into Vitamin "§cCarbos§r."

You think Tamato berries are a rare drop of one of the bug Pokemon, probably §aBlipbug§r and its evolutionary line. You seem to remember they are a treetop Pokemon. Perhaps something in your explorers notes will help.
Offer some materials associated with health and sickness to Arceus.

§cPomeg §rberries should do the same thing as all the other following berries, but they don't. They can't be made into "HP-UP," Sitrus berries do that. But they can be used to decrease a Pokemon's Health EVs, so they are still important. 

You think Pomeg berries can rarely be found carried by wild §7Pidove, §rand you suspect a few may have survived because of their superior homing capabilities. §rYou might have to look through your explorers notes to see if you can find them.

Offer some materials associated with resiliency and dissolution to Arceus.
Offer some materials associated with ingeniousity and foolishness to Arceus.
Offer some materials associated with cleverness and laziness to Arceus.

Before using Rock Smash to break ores, try it out on a block of stone. If it does not drop cobble, IT IS BUGGED, so use it for farming items/encounters only, and not to break ore. You are reluctant to place or break some of the §dore§r you have uncovered, because you remember that your ancestors would use instruments with §9'Fortune'§r enchantments on them to get the best yield for break.

Well you don't have access to those fancy enchantments right now, but you do remember one thing: When Pokemon break a block with §o§c§crocksmash§r, it counts as if breaking that ore with a §bFortune II§r pickaxe! However, there are other possible effects of rocksmash- it could reveal an item, or start a combat with a pokemon uncovered from within the rock!

Even so, you are willing to give it a try. Arceus was willing to give you the information you needed to teach 'Rain dance' to your Pokemon. Perhaps if you make an offering of things that remind you of 'Rock Smash', he will help you?

While Drifloon can't learn Rocksmash, lots of Pokemon can! Including some of Arceus's gifted baby pokemon, like Sudowoodo!

The §9Cooking Pot§r is an item for creating §cCurry§r. Curry is for creating miraculous food! With §aten berries§r, a cheap base item like §lBrittle Bones§r, and the patience to slowly fan and stir the curry- no smoke, no spilling! -you can make a mighty §cCopperaja Class §rcurry. Even with few to no berries and plenty of mistakes, curry still has healing properties!

Copperaja Class curry will heal a pokemon, give them almost 2000 XP, cure all status, restore all move PP, §oand§r give a Pokemon §d50 happiness§r.

Given the large amount of baby Pokemon Arceus wants you to raise, that 50 happiness will be extremely helpful!

The only problem?

Cooking Pots have to be made of cast §eiron§r to distribute heat evenly. You are going to need a lot of iron before you will be able to make a cooking pot, and then another bar of iron to make a §cflint and steel§r, because fire charges are too unpredictable to light them. 

However! It's still worth noting that you'll one day have a §dpowerful tool §rfor everything from healing to happiness to xp-training weak Pokemon!

Brittle Bones are the easiest resource for you to get ahold of. All you have to do is find a Pokemon who drops bone, or gather them from a ground tile. Then put the bone in a furnace and cook to create brittle bones.

You are very lonely. 

Your Pokemon help a lot, but none of them can talk back to you, and you miss your family. Well. Some of your family. 

But yesterday, you woke up with a horrible, amazing idea:

§cYou think you know might where to find other people. §r

Not here! Not in this endless... withered... ghostly emptiness. Even if there were other people here, you could fly for a thousand miles and never find them. 

No, you know a condensed, concentrated place that might still be §cbelow§r all this, below the emptiness of the missing surface crust, down where the center of the Earth (hopefully) still might §cburn§r. 

You need to go take a peek inside the Nether.

Maybe, just maybe, if they're even down there... Maybe you can bring someone §dhome§r with you.
This quest will cause the Rock Smash to become available the first time the player is holding a block that could benefit from Fortune.

It is important to be able to §9§cChange the Weather§r, because sometimes pokemon are only availale to you during rain or sunshine. For example! Lamp pokemon are frightened of rain. 

Although there might be a Pokeball around here somewhere to try catching a Castiform with, that's not a surefire recipe for success. Fortunately, Drifloon is also a balloon Pokemon, just like Castiform, and while it might not specifically be a Weather Balloon, it can learn §cSunny Day§r. 

§r...That is, if you have a TM to teach it with. If you're desperate for sunshine, the only thing to do might be to pray to Arceus and offer him some relevant gifts.

'Hail' can't change the weather the way Rainy Day and Sunny Day can, but it's another form of weather you might want to have access to. Arceus seems to think having access to weather changes can help you terrorform this empty void.

'Sandstorm' can't change the weather the way Rainy Day and Sunny Day can, but Arceus seems to think having access to weather changes can help you terrorform this empty void. A sandstorm is a mix of wind and grit!

If you want a chance at surviving in the Nether, you are going to need to prepare for the journey.

First, you are going to need potions of §cFire Resistance§r, and you should make sure that they're 8-minute potions, too, just to be safe To brew such a potion you will need...

[§aEASY§r] A Fire-Proof Cauldron or Brewing Stand
[      ] Magma Cream
         [      ] Slime
         [§aEASY§r] Blaze Powder
[§aEASY§r] Nether Wart

You have access to very few fire-proof Pokemon, so it is best for their sake that you prepare a number of §9§aBurn Heals.§r, either using a cauldron or using a brewing stand.

If you §cdo§r find someone in the Nether... they may not be §cthemselves§r anymore. You need to prepare for the possibility that rescuing a soul from the Nether might be very difficult, and that the soul itself might be very dangerous. 

Prepare three splash potions of weakness. Ensure that they are modified to work for an extra long span of time, so you have plenty of time to act!

You recall that your gran owned a Tauros who knew §eHeadbutt§r.

Headbutt is an ability that can be used to dislodge Pokemon- and rare items- from trees. Certain Pokemon can learn Headbutt naturally, including some of the available §dBaby Pokemon!§r

These include §9Mantyke,§r whom you can get with Magost Berries through the Wave incense, and §bSnorunt§r, whom you can get with a Dawn Stone shard.

If you want to catch a Pokemon that can learn Headbutt, you know the following can all learn it:

Snubbull
Cubone
Aron
Roggenrola
Dewpider
and even Castiform!

§5But be careful§r! If you catch your Pokemon at too high a level, or forget to learn Headbutt or delete it, you won't be able to get it back, and will have to raise up another Pokemon!

If you can manage to use Headbutt to collect some gifts to offer Arceus, you're sure he'll reward you by making it easier to teach Headbutt to Pokemon in the future!

There are four kinds of §ebitter medicine§r which Pokemon hate to eat, but which have very strong healing powers.

The first of these medicines is §aEnergy Powder§r which can be made with §93 Oran Berries §r(or 1 Strius Berry or 1 Heartbeet), a piece of §epaper§r, and a §dghast tear§r.

The second kind of §ebitter medicine§r is §eHeal Powder§r, which can cure any status effect. Although it is very bitter, it is sometimes convenient to carry around only one stack of identical medications, instead of fooling around with five different kinds of berries. 

To make Heal Powder, you will need one kind of each §cstatus curing berry§r, one §dDeathbloom§r to dehydrate the berries, and a piece of §epaper§r.

The third kind of §ebitter medicine§r is the §eEnergy Root§r, which can heal massive amounts of damage, as much as a hyper potion! 

To make an Energy Root, you will need §lbonemeal§r, a §a§apungent root§r§r which can be made with carrots and a few other supplies, a §c§cheartbeet§r, a §dwithered bone§r, and some §epaper§r.

The forth kind of §ebitter medicine§r is the §aRevival Herb§r, which can revive a fainted Pokemon. This is the hardest medicine your Nana taught you to make, and also the most important, because you are unable to make traditional revives. 

To make a Revival Herb, you will need §lstring§r and two §egold nuggets§r to bind the herb, three pieces of §asheared grass§r, an §capple§r, a §cfermented spiders eye§r, and §ddeathbloom§r. §a§a

You miss your Nana, who taught you how to make all these herbal medicines; but through you, her knowledge lives on. 

Still, sometimes when times are tough, you need to let out the bad energy somehow. Venting into the void can help!

If you want a chance at surviving in the Nether, you may want to bring some type of weapon. Iron weapons are too expensive for you right now, but you can use §bcrystals§r to create a sword of comparative power! (Amethyst works too!)

You have many options for a set of armor, headed into the Nether. The cheapest is probably a set of clay paneled armor, but you can also create armor out of leather, or cheap gems like crystal or amethyst. Maybe you can even dress up as a scary 'bad guy' team from eras past, to make you feel tougher!

It is possible to make armor out of clay tiles. It is not particularly strong, similar to running around with stones strapped to one's body, but it is easier to obtain the ingredients for than Leather Armor.
As soon as you are able to harvest Geodudes regularly, you are capable of making a full set of §7stone tools.

Have a look at the evolutionary items that could help unlock!

When Pokemon break a block with §o§c§cRock Smash§r, it utterly destroys the block, but often reveals a rare and unexpected item was hidden inside, or starts a combat!

The problem is, you don't have any Pokemon that learn rock smash naturally.
